    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and trace.csv. For metric.csv, compute and return: (1) list of unique cmdb_id with counts, (2) list of unique kpi_name with counts (top 20 by count), and (3) overall min(timestamp) and max(timestamp). For trace.csv, compute and return: (1) unique cmdb_id with counts, (2) unique trace_name with counts (top 20), and (3) overall min(timestamp) and max(timestamp). Keep outputs compact and limited to the aggregates requested (no raw full time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output: metric.csv contains 56 unique cmdb_id values (including db_001..db_013 and many os_* nodes) and 132 unique KPI names; its time coverage in Asia/Shanghai is 2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00 through 2020-05-26 05:00:00+08:00. trace.csv contains 9 cmdb_id values (docker_* and os_021/os_022), 72 trace names, and covers 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00 through 2020-05-26 04:59:00+08:00. The incident window (2020-05-26 04:30 to 05:00) is fully inside both files' ranges (metric covers full hour; trace covers the incident window). Next we must compute global thresholds (before filtering) for each component-KPI time series, then extract incident-window points and detect anomalies. No anomaly detection has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each component (cmdb_id) and KPI (kpi_name) present in metric.csv: (1) compute global P95 and P5 from the full available series and store this thresholds table in a kernel variable named thresholds_df; (2) then filter metric.csv to the incident window May 26, 2020 from 04:30:00 to 05:00:00 Asia/Shanghai and for each component-KPI compute: total points in window, number of anomalies where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5, and the earliest anomaly timestamp (as datetime in Asia/Shanghai). Return a compact table of the top 20 component-KPIs ranked by anomaly count, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI. Also return the total number of metric anomalies found across all component-KPIs in the window. Store the filtered incident-window metric rows in a kernel variable named incident_metric_df but do not print full raw series. Limit printed rows to the requested top-20 aggregate table."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the last Executor result we have a metric-level anomaly summary for the incident window (2020-05-26 04:30 to 05:00 Asia/Shanghai). Key observations: (1) A large number of metric anomaly points were detected in-window (total_anomalies = 25054). (2) Many component-KPI pairs show every point in the window anomalous (e.g., db_001 and db_002 have 30/30 anomalous points for multiple KPIs; several os_* and osb_001 entries show 31/31). These full-window anomalies are strong fault candidates. (3) We have stored thresholds_df (global P95/P5 per component-KPI), incident_metric_df (filtered rows in the incident window), and top20_df (top component-KPIs by anomaly count). Next we must convert per-point anomalies into 'fault' intervals (consecutive anomaly runs), remove isolated spikes, compute severity of each fault (how far it breaches its threshold), and produce a compact ranked list of faults so we can localize the root cause component and time. No trace analysis has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel variables thresholds_df and incident_metric_df, build a faults table as follows: (1) Mark each incident_metric_df row as anomalous if value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5 (join thresholds_df on cmdb_id and kpi_name to get global_p95 and global_p5). (2) For each cmdb_id + kpi_name, sort by timestamp and group consecutive anomalous points into fault sequences (consecutive means timestamps increasing by the sampling interval present in the data; you may assume a 60-second step but detect actual step from data). For each fault sequence compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, start_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, end_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, num_points, duration_seconds, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5. (3) Compute a severity metric per fault sequence: if the fault is above threshold (values >= global_p95) set severity_pct = 100 * (max_value - global_p95) / max(abs(global_p95), 1e-9); if below threshold (values <= global_p5) set severity_pct = 100 * (global_p5 - min_value) / max(abs(global_p5), 1e-9). (4) Filter out sequences that are isolated spikes: keep only sequences with num_points >= 2 AND severity_pct > 50. (5) Return a compact table of the top 20 fault sequences sorted by severity_pct descending, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, end_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, num_points, duration_seconds, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5, severity_pct. Also store the full faults table in the kernel as faults_df and return the total number of fault sequences found (after filtering). Limit printed rows to the top-20 table only."
}

{
    "analysis": "From previous steps we computed metric thresholds, flagged per-point anomalies in the incident window, grouped consecutive anomalies into 101 fault sequences (filtered by >=2 points and severity_pct>50), and did trace-level thresholding/aggregation. Key observations so far: (1) Many node-level KPIs (os_*) show full-window disk I/O anomalies starting at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00. (2) Many DB KPIs across db_* nodes also show consistent anomalies in the same window (AIOS, tnsping_result_time, LFSync/Write rates). (3) Trace anomalies are concentrated on docker_* containers and on self.* error_rate traces; many trace anomalies also start at 04:30:00+08:00. (4) When faults occur at different levels, we must pick the level with the most significant deviation from thresholds; among allowed components, os_* entries (e.g., os_022, os_001, os_020, os_021, os_002) show the largest severities and earliest start times. However, we need to confirm which single component (from allowed lists) is most likely the root cause by combining fault severity, earliest occurrence time, and its presence in trace anomalies (to ensure propagation to services/containers). Current data suggests node-level disk I/O degradation starting at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00 (not yet finalized to a single node).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using kernel variables faults_df and incident_trace_df: \n1) Aggregate faults_df by cmdb_id (only include cmdb_ids that start with 'os_', 'docker_', or 'db_') and compute for each cmdb_id: number_of_fault_sequences, max_severity_pct, earliest_fault_start_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, total_fault_points (sum of num_points). Return a compact table of the top 20 cmdb_id sorted by max_severity_pct (columns: cmdb_id, number_of_fault_sequences, total_fault_points, earliest_fault_start_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, max_severity_pct). Store this table as comp_fault_agg in the kernel. \n2) From that aggregated result, take the top 5 cmdb_id (by max_severity_pct). For each of these top-5, compute trace involvement from incident_trace_df: count of trace anomaly rows where cmdb_id equals that component, and earliest trace anomaly datetime for that component (earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI). Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_anomaly_count, earliest_trace_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI for these top-5. \nLimit outputs to those two compact tables (top-20 component fault-agg and top-5 trace involvement)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds for metrics and traces, filtered to the incident window (2020-05-26 04:30–05:00 Asia/Shanghai), detected per-point anomalies, grouped consecutive anomalies into fault sequences and filtered to plausible faults (>=2 points and severity_pct>50). Aggregate results show widespread metric faults across many os_* nodes and many db_* nodes starting at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00. Trace anomalies are concentrated on docker_* containers and on self.* error_rate traces; importantly, os_022 stands out as a high-severity metric offender and also has substantial trace anomalies (trace involvement count=171 with earliest anomaly at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00). os_001 also shows very high metric severity but appears to have no trace anomalies in the incident window (trace_anomaly_count=0). According to the root-cause rules: if multiple faulty components exist at different levels, pick the level with the most significant deviation; when multiple at the same level, use traces to pick the downstream faulty component. Here we have many node-level faults; os_022 is a predominant node with both high metric severity and trace anomalies starting exactly at the window start, which strongly suggests it is the single root cause candidate. The likely reason from the metric patterns (Disk_io_util, Disk_rd_ios, Disk_avgqu_sz, CPU_iowait_time abnormalities across os_022 and across other os_* nodes and downstream DB KPIs) is node-level disk I/O degradation leading to elevated IO waits and impacting database operations/traces. However, to finalize root cause component, exact occurrence time, and reason we should extract compact per-KPI evidence for os_022 (counts, earliest anomaly time, extremal values, P95/P5) and confirm trace anomaly names/timestamps for os_022 to show propagation. No log files are available yet, so metrics+traces must suffice for localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id == 'os_022' only, using incident_metric_df joined with thresholds_df: (1) produce a compact per-kpi summary table (limit 20 rows) with columns: kpi_name, points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_p95 OR <= global_p5), earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5. Sort by anomaly_count desc then by kpi_name. (2) Also, from incident_trace_df produce a compact trace-aggregate for os_022 (limit top 20 by anomaly_count) with columns: trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI. Return both tables only and store them in the kernel as os022_metric_agg and os022_trace_agg. Keep outputs bounded to those two compact tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the diagnosis workflow: computed global thresholds for metrics and traces, filtered to the incident window (2020-05-26 04:30–05:00 Asia/Shanghai), detected anomalies, grouped consecutive anomalous points into fault sequences, and aggregated faults by component. Results show many node-level faults across os_* hosts and DB faults across db_* hosts beginning at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00. Aggregation by component ranked os_022 highest by max severity_pct and it also has substantial trace anomalies (171 trace anomaly rows, earliest at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00). Detailed os_022 per-KPI aggregates show simultaneous full-window anomalies for Disk_io_util, Disk_rd_ios, Disk_rd_kbs, Disk_svctm (high svctm, many anomalous points) plus Agent_ping and ICMP_ping; os_022 trace aggregates show many error_rate anomalies (trace.from_root.osb.error_rate, trace.self.csf.error_rate) and remoteprocess error rates to docker_001 and docker_002, all starting at 04:30:00+08:00. According to the localization rules: multiple node-level faults were identified but os_022 is the predominant node (highest severity and trace involvement). Thus os_022 is the top root-cause candidate and the fault begins at 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00. The metric pattern (high Disk_io_util, high Disk_svctm, Disk_avgqu_sz and increased CPU iowait) indicates node-level I/O degradation causing request errors; mapping to the allowed reason categories, the closest match is a CPU-related fault manifesting as high iowait (i.e., 'CPU fault'). However, before finalizing, we should confirm the exact earliest anomaly timestamps across all os_022 KPIs and traces and collect top KPI/trace evidence for a final statement.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id == 'os_022' only, compute and return a compact evidence report: (1) earliest_metric_anomaly_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI = the earliest datetime in the incident window when any os_022 metric row was flagged anomalous (using thresholds_df). (2) earliest_trace_anomaly_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI = the earliest datetime in the incident window when any os_022 trace row was flagged anomalous (using thresholds_trace_df). (3) Top 5 os_022 KPIs by anomaly_count: for each return kpi_name, points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI, max_value, global_p95, global_p5. (4) Top 5 os_022 trace series by anomaly_count: for each return trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anom_datetime_ASIA_SHANGHAI. Limit output to these two compact tables and the two earliest-anomaly datetimes; store them as os022_evidence_df (KPIs), os022_trace_evidence_df (traces), and os022_earliest_times in the kernel. Do not print raw time series beyond these summaries."
}

